  "text": "ZORRO was developed primarily as a cipher that could be masked easily for higher order masking by reducing the total number of non-linear operations in the cipher. The structure is very similar to AES with the main difference being the values of the S-Box and number of bytes substituted with the SBox values, both designed to reduce the level of non-linearity thus making the masking of the cipher easier. Other differences between ZORRO and AES is the absence of the KeySchedule, with the same key being used for each round, the round counter is also x-ored into the state after ShiftRows. To account for the lower security of the changed SBox and absence of the KeySchedule, 24 rounds are implemented instead of the 10 for AES [CITATION_1] .",
